******************************************
A Chaebol=E2=80=99s Fast Rise and Even Faster Fall
******************************************

South Korea's Yulsan Group (=EC=9C=A8=EC=82=B0=EA=B7=B8=EB=A3=B9) really sp=
eed-ran the rise and fall of a business empire. Founded in 1975 with nothin=
g. Two years later, $165 million in export revenue. 14 subsidiaries, 8,000 =
employees. A year after that, bankrupt. In this video, the story of a chaeb=
ol. They never even made it five years.

-----------------------
Exports Exports Exports
-----------------------

Throughout the 1950s, the South Korean economy struggled. Growth was errati=
c, the currency overvalued, and the economy primarily relied upon foreign a=
id, mining and agriculture. The country's primary economic policy goal was =
to reduce its dependency on imports, so building up domestic industry and k=
eeping high tariffs. This is generally known as =E2=80=9Cimport substitutio=
n=E2=80=9D. The government had some preferential export promotion measures,=
 since it brought in valuable foreign exchange. But on the whole they cared=
 more about import substitution, much like other developing countries in La=
tin America and South Asia at the time. Then in 1961, Park Chung-hee took o=
ver and instituted a radically different direction - an export-led growth s=
trategy. Like any great successes, it had many fathers - lessons from Japan=
's similar experience. Plus Korea=E2=80=99s lack of natural resources, smal=
l domestic market, its need to generate foreign currency, a desire to relie=
ve pressure from the Americans. So on. To encourage exports, the government=
 harmonized the complicated exchange rate system - removing incentives to i=
mport. They lifted tariffs on - and then gave tax exemptions for - intermed=
iate goods used to produce future exports. In other words, import as much a=
s you like, as long as you use that to make exports. And the government set=
 up a financing system to offer working capital financing at subsidized rat=
es. And finally, Park Chung-hee's government encouraged the educated Korean=
 populace to be entrepreneurial - praising those who succeeded in doing so.=
 Exports over the 1960s and 1970s boomed, driving impressive economic growt=
h. But the obsession with exports and the Wild Wild West business culture o=
f 1970s Korea also led to some unusual happenings.

----------
Beginnings
----------

Shin Sun-ho (=EC=8B=A0=EC=84=A0=ED=98=B8) was born in 1947. The sixth of se=
ven sons to a well-respected and educated man who had worked in finance and=
 land reform. Several of Shin's brothers got PhDs at Harvard and MIT, becom=
ing professors and deans. In a way, they inspired the soft-spoken and intro=
verted Shin to do business:

"All my brothers are considerable successes as scholars and teachers, but I=
 saw that they had to give up valuable pursuits because of circumstantial l=
imits ... I concluded that only business is limitless"

Shin studied applied mathematics at the elite Seoul National University and=
 was a participant in student activitism. After graduating and completing h=
is three years of military service, he started working as a sales salaryman=
 brokering import-export business deals. He then founded Yulsan Industry wi=
th his wife in September 1974 - reporting a minimum capital of about a mill=
ion won or $2,000 to avoid fees. Later media reports of Shin founding it wi=
th his friends or with just $2,000 were said by him to be false. The compan=
y got its name from the nickname of Shin's father. It literally means Chest=
nut mountain. Yulsan began in a shabby hole-in-the-wall in Seoul with nothi=
ng more than a telephone and desk. Shin ran around looking for ways to make=
 money. Just another small business amongst many.

-----------------
Letters of Credit
-----------------

In February 1975, Yulsan moved to a new building. There, Shin came across a=
 bunch of documents sent from Kuwait by a guy named Won Gil-nam. Won is a K=
orean citizen. But after spending time as the first secretary-general of a =
Korean-Islamic relations association, he moved to Kuwait and joined their g=
overnment within their Ministry of Communications. Thanks to the oil crises=
, the countries of Middle East like Kuwait were building lots of infrastruc=
ture but needed materials. So Won started a business and issued several "le=
tters of credit" to potential suppliers back home. These documents essentia=
lly said that a Kuwaiti importer can guarantee payment for building materia=
ls if those materials can be delivered to them in Kuwait. Other Korean comp=
anies received the letters first but didn=E2=80=99t see the work as particu=
larly profitable. The prices were low, and companies worried about the risk=
 of unloading at the Middle East's then-undeveloped ports. Imagine getting =
held up at the ports - in 40 degree Celsius heat - waiting to unload. Somet=
imes for as long as a month! Not only that, you incur what are called demur=
rage fees, penalties when a cargo gets stuck at port. So the letters of cre=
dit passed around until finally landing at Yulsan's doorstep. Where others =
saw bad business, Shin saw an opportunity. In June 1975, he recruited some =
of his school friends and registered a new Yulsan trading company to take o=
n the job.

-------------
The Big Break
-------------

Thanks to the government=E2=80=99s export-oriented policies, Yulsan can use=
 the Kuwaiti letters of credit as collateral for a short-term, 90 day bank =
loan for up to 86% of the deal's value. Even better, the loan=E2=80=99s int=
erest rate was subsidized. Normal bank loans' interest rates were from 19-2=
5%. An export loan had a rate of just 9%. Great. But how to make money when=
 the prices offered by the Kuwaiti importers were so low? And how to avoid =
getting detained at the Middle Eastern ports? Shin decided to charter his o=
wn ships himself for the most favorable rates. Yulsan rented a 14,000 ton s=
hip named the Ocean Dragon, filled it with leftover building materials like=
 cement, plywood and steel rebar, and went to Kuwait. That was the beginnin=
g of a business. To ensure that their Middle Eastern customers got their sh=
ipments in time, Yulsan commissioned helicopters and bought scrapped landin=
g crafts from Hong Kong to unload the ships as fast as possible. They pulle=
d out every possible stop. The story goes that one time, the Yulsan people =
bribed their ship's captain to set fire to piles of wet burlap bags stacked=
 on the deck - knowing that the Saudi port authorities would prioritize doc=
king a ship seemingly on fire. These acts of daring worked. In its first si=
x months of operations over the second half of 1975, Yulsan reported $3.4 m=
illion in export revenues - mostly cement.

----------------
A Shopping Spree
----------------

In its first year of operations, Yulsan started buying new businesses. They=
 targeted bankrupt businesses that had been seized by the banks. The first =
acquisition in late December 1975 was the insolvent Shinjin Aluminum (=EC=
=8B=A0=EC=A7=84=EC=95=8C=EB=AF=B8=EB=8A=84) company. Shinjin had been found=
ed by the Korean automotive pioneer Kim Chang-won to supply aluminium sashe=
s for the larger Shinjin Automobile company. They were losing a billion won=
 a year - about $2 million in 1975 dollars. Which is why Yulsan only had to=
 pay half of that to acquire them. Nevertheless, a newly-founded company bu=
ying a company with such a storied name - and then giving it their own name=
 - was what first put Yulsan on the map. But Yulsan was just getting starte=
d. In April 1976, they acquired the insolvent Geumyong Shipping company, re=
named that to Yulsan Shipping to fuel their exports business. That same yea=
r, they also acquired the Dongwon Construction company, renaming it to Yuls=
an Construction. This let Yulsan take on full-scale construction projects a=
t home and overseas. In its first full year, 1976, Yulsan's export revenues=
 grew 12-times over to $42 million. The growth caught the attention of the =
Korean government. Pleased that Yulsan was doing so well in helping to fulf=
ill the country's export goals, the government awarded them a prestigious i=
ndustrial medal.

-----------------------
General Trading Company
-----------------------

Yulsan continued its tear of acquisitions in 1977, adding eight more compan=
ies. Some of these companies seemed quite distant from exporting building m=
aterials. For example, Yulsan bought the Kyungheung Trading company, a text=
iles manufacturer, and started a clothing line called "Bambim" (=EB=B0=A4=
=EB=B9=94). They also bought - among other things - a tourism business that=
 started off giving tours to Yulsan's technical staff. A shoes company. A h=
otel. Even an industrial college. About a third of their money was spent on=
 acquiring land, some 660,000 to 990,000 square meters of then unused land =
in Seoul. For the 1977 year, the Yulsan Group generated $165 million in exp=
ort revenues. The company's management gained renown around Korea for their=
 boldness and aggression. Shin treated it all as a game, really. In a rare =
interview with the Times in July 1978, Shin said:

Money was not my objective. To be more precise, I do not love it ... I 'pla=
y' business like sport.

By spring 1978, the Yulsan Group owned 14 businesses, employed 8,000 people=
, and had total assets worth about $230 million. They were in the midst of =
acquiring electronics, machinery, and petrochemicals companies too. That ye=
ar, the Korean government designated Yulsan a "General Trading Company". Th=
ese were Korea's version of Japan's Soga Shosha, famous massive companies t=
hat trade all sorts of goods wholesale. It was a prestigious label that onl=
y 12 other companies in South Korea had - companies like Samsung, Hyundai, =
and Samhwa.

----
Debt
----

From the start, Yulsan Group borrowed ferociously to acquire its various bu=
sinesses. Plenty of Korean companies in that time racked up huge amounts of=
 debt. Yulsan just did it faster, harder and flashier than everyone else. A=
t the start of 1978, they had a staggering 27 times more debt than sharehol=
ders' equity. The average general trading company, on the other hand, had j=
ust 4.9 times more debt than equity. The real core issue for the Yulsan Gro=
up however was that much of that debt was short term debt. The aforemention=
ed 3 month export loan that used a letter of credit as its sole collateral.=
 With two-thirds of Yulsan's assets tied up in illiquid real estate or inve=
ntory, the group=E2=80=99s lifeblood was tied to its exports. Without growi=
ng export revenues, they cannot get the short-term funding they need to sta=
y alive.

--------
The Turn
--------

In July 1978, literally as that praise-filled Times article printed, it all=
 came crashing down. Earlier in the spring of that year, the Saudi Arabian =
government caught Yulsan Group doing some wholesale distribution and retail=
. This was illegal for foreigners and Yulsan got a fine. That was the end o=
f that. But either accidentally or maliciously, the news spread amidst the =
South Koreans back home that Yulsan had been entirely banned from Saudi Ara=
bia. Banks and financial companies were suddenly less willing to loan money=
. However, the most devastating hit was in August, when the Park government=
 announced measures to suppress real estate speculation, the 8-8 measures. =
One of which was a ban on the exports of building materials to support a bi=
g apartment construction effort. The 8-8 measures also smashed the real est=
ate market. Yulsan could not sell any units from a recent apartment project=
 its construction company completed. Nor could it unload the real estate it=
 had bought up during the initial run up in prices. And now that their cash=
 cow building exports were banned, the company missed its 1978 export goal =
of $400 million, only generating $150 million in sales. The export credits =
dried up.

--------
Collapse
--------

Its short-term funding now gone, Yulsan started melting down. In September =
1978, Yulsan requested help from its main bank, Seoul Bank and Trust. The b=
ank along with two others provided 7 billion won or about $14 million in 19=
78 US Dollars to try and save the company. It did not. In November 1978, Yu=
lsan announced that it would sell seven of its affiliated companies includi=
ng its electronics, leather, and chemicals businesses. The checks began to =
bounce. Desperate, the Yulsan people allegedly turned to fraud. They had th=
eir overseas entities issue false letters of credit for special commodities=
 - which were actually ordinary rocks. The letters were then used for more =
short-term export loans. Then in 1979, things got weird. On January 25th 19=
79, Shin Sun-ho receives a call from someone claiming to be from the Blue H=
ouse, the presidential office, summoning him to the Economic Planning Burea=
u office. Shin cannot ignore the call and so travels to the EPB, where he i=
s picked up by another car. But when the car starts traveling away from the=
 Blue House, Shin gets suspicious. He leaps out the back door at a toll boo=
th gate and hides, barely escaping the kidnapping attempt. He then reports =
his ordeal to the press - perhaps implying that the kidnappers were somehow=
 associated with the government. As rumor has it, this sets off someone in =
the actual government. A week afterwards, Shin and his team worked out a 9 =
billion won ($18 million dollar) financing plan with his creditors to bridg=
e the company and give it more time to get on to solid ground. Then without=
 warning, the plan is vetoed by someone at the highest levels of power. Wit=
h that, Yulsan's fate was guaranteed. The business goes bankrupt. And in Ap=
ril 1979, the 31-year old Shin - along an aide and a bank official - were a=
rrested. The Korean government reassured antsy foreign investors - Bank of =
America somehow was owed $5 million - by announcing that all of Yulsan's ~$=
310 million (150 billion won) of loans will be repaid. The group=E2=80=99s =
various bits are stripped apart and almost all of its assets seized. The go=
vernment also promised more stringent checks on the issuance of these short=
-term export bank loans so that another Yulsan cannot use them again to boo=
tstrap their way to heaven. In November 1979, the lauded business prodigy S=
hin was sentenced to several years in jail for embezzlement and fraud. His =
legal ordeal lasted for several years until 1985, when he finally completed=
 his partially-suspended sentence and probation.

----------
Conclusion
----------

Democracy advocate Kim Dae-jung later wrote that Korean president Park Chun=
g-hee himself was the power who took down the flashy Shin Sun-ho. That Park=
 had been the one who nixed the final rescue plan to save the collapsing gr=
oup in February 1979. When asked in an interview 20 years later about who w=
as responsible for Yulsan's collapse, Shin smiled and said "Does it matter =
who it was now? Let's forgive our enemies". Maybe there was some malicious =
power behind the scenes of it all. But considering the company's massive de=
bts and near-total dependence on 3-month export credits, I don't fault Park=
 or anyone else in the government for thinking that it would be better to j=
ust let these guys go. So Yulsan sank into oblivion but Shin somehow manage=
d to make a comeback. Before the bankruptcy, the Seoul city government acqu=
ired some of the land Yulsan bought to build the current Supreme Court buil=
ding in Seocho. They gave in exchange two new lots. The first lot was taken=
 over by Lotte and now hosts Lotte World, the massive mall and theme park. =
After Shin returned to Yulsan, he developed the second lot - which the cred=
itors could not seize thanks to circumstances and a contract quirk - into w=
hat is now the Central City commercial area and bus terminal in Seoul. It o=
pened in 2000, having endured great turmoil including even the Asian Financ=
ial Crisis in the 1990s. The department store chaebol Shinsegae later bough=
t into the complex in 2012. And in 2014, Shin was reported as having a net =
worth of $750 million - one of Korea's richest men. A happy ending. I suppo=
se.

